================================================================================
VERDICT: Testing Grok's Claim
================================================================================

Grok's claim: "Star constraints propagate the dependence across adjacent TTs
in the low-dim space (≤3 basis), making pre-flip indep generator Q-redundant
while new TTs absorb into higher filtration."

This predicts:
1. Destroyed TTs are boundary-redundant given kept TTs (star propagation)
2. Created TTs add NO new boundary dimensions (absorb into higher filtration)
3. The net effect is a rank drop of exactly 1 in im(∂₂)

EVIDENCE FROM n=5:
  Prediction 1 (destroyed redundant given K): False
    Counterexamples: 120
    T2: destroyed_redundant=[False, False, False, False, False, False]
    T5: destroyed_redundant=[False, False, False, False, False, False]
    T11: destroyed_redundant=[False, False, False, False, False, False]
  Prediction 2 (created redundant given K): False
    Counterexamples: 120
    T2: created_redundant=[False, False, False, False, False, False]
    T5: created_redundant=[False, False, False, False, False, False]
    T11: created_redundant=[False, False, False, False, False, False]
  Prediction 3 (rank drop = 1): False
    Rank drops observed: [0]

  ACTUAL MECHANISM:
    dim(B_kept) = dim(B_old) always? False
    dim(B_kept) = dim(B_new) always? False
    dim(B_kept) < dim(B_old) always? True
    dim(B_kept) < dim(B_new) always? True

Done.
